description: 1968 Dodge D-100 Pickup Truck -Restored
as presented by...
Garrett Classics
1865 McGee Lane Suite F-G
Lewisville, Texas, 75077

Garrett Classics is proud to showcase this classic '68 Dodge D-100 Utiline Pickup Truck. This interesting truck was owned by the original family since new until recently. This truck underwent an extensive restoration effort involving removal of all body panels from the chassis to accomplish a long-term restoration. Always a dry climate, never any rust on this one.  It is in fine operating condition and a real pleasure to drive. It had a new set of Michelin tires installed all around recently. The wood in the bed was replaced during the restoration as well. This truck spent most of its years in the New Braunfels, Texas area. Today, this D-100 is proudly displayed here at Garrett Classics in Lewisville, Texas.
FEATURES INCLUDE :
225 cubic inch 140HP Slant Six Engine
3-Speed Manual Column-Shift Transmission
New Alternator
New Carburetor
Utiline DODGE Design
Body Off Chassis Restoration
One-Family Texas Owned & Operated Truck
(current owner recently bought it at auction)
Factory Steel Wheels w New Michelin Tires
Wood Bed w Wood Rails
Correct Color-Keyed Bumpers & Grille
Air Conditioning - Needs Completion, compressor underhood
You don't see many of these Dodge Utiline Design trucks on the road anymore, you especially don't see one in this condition. Dodge produced this design of truck from 1961 until 1971.
The paint and body show very well. The body panels were removed during the extensive restoration efforts.

The interior is spartan and correct, displaying the original gauge cluster with functional gauges. Also, the 3-speed manual shifter on the column works as it should. Note the clean dash, door panels, and headliner.

Under the hood is the famous for its longevity Dodge Slant Six engine. This power plant runs smooth and strong. An air conditioning compressor is there but the system needs parts and work to make this an A/C truck. Close inspection will confirm good sheet metal throughout the firewall, inner fenders and core support.
The undercarriage is in very good condition. This is a driven truck, clean and solid underneath.

The wood bed & color-keyed strips are in great shape as well. Enjoy the remaining photos and  to view more, just click on any one of the photos here to be directed to the entire album. Again feel free to contact Dave at 241-213-7072 or Maris at 214-616-2317 with any questions.

description: The Dodge Challenger is the name of three different generations and was marketed by the Dodge division of Chrysler. The Dodge Silver Challenger was first to be produced from 1958 to 1959 as a limited edition which inherited its name from the fact that they didn't use any other paint choice except silver. From 1969 to 1974, the first generation Dodge Challenger pony car was built using the Chrysler E-Platform, sharing most of its major components with the Plymouth Barracuda. The second generation which was in production from 1978 to 1983, was a badge Mitsubishi Galant Lambda. The third and current generation was introduced in early 2008 as a rival to the competition, the fifth generation for both, the Ford Mustang and Chevrolet Camaro.

GR Auto Gallery is pleased to present this 1973 Dodge Challenger for consideration. According to the owner, this vehicle has received a full restoration back in 2005 by West Side Auto. It also features a 1970 340 Cuda Motor with 360 heads (ported and polished), 10-1 forged pistons, 10-10 steel crank, 509 lift-292 duration cam HYD, newer double roller timing chain, 750 dual feed double pumper with a manual secondary holly carb. The rear quarter panels have been replaced, front fenders have been repaired, newer vinyl top, upgraded MSD ignition and X-Pipe Flow Master exhaust. The exterior paint is finished in “Brandy Candy” by House of Colors, the paint is in great shape besides a few dings and scratches. The interior is in fair condition and appears to have newer vinyl on the seats, the door panels need to be refinished due to sun fading and chipping. According to our intake inspection, low beams, high beams, tail lights, turn signals, fog lights, hood and trunk latches, locks and windows work as they should, the radio has been upgraded to and aftermarket unit and works great. Please call or email us today for more information on this 1973 Dodge Challenger.
To see over 80 photos of this car, including under carriage please visit our website www.grautogallery.com

description: Worldwide Vintage Autos is pleased to present this 1973 Dodge Challenger. We scour the country for vintage cars and trucks and we rarely come across one like this! You must see and drive this rare Challenger!  HISTORY   The Challenger was available as a two-door in either a hardtop coupe or a convertible body design, and in two models for its introductory year. The base model was the "Challenger" with either a I6 or V8 engine, as well as a "Challenger R/T" that included a 383 cu in (6.28 L) V8. The Special Edition or "Challenger SE" that added a number of appearance, convenience, and comfort items was "available as a model in either the Challenger R/T or Challenger." The standard engine on the base model was the 225 cu in (3.7 L) six-cylinder. The standard engine on the V8 was the 230 bhp (171.5 kW) 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 with a 2-barrel carburetor. For 1970, the optional engines included the 340 and 383 cu in (5.6 and 6.3 L), as well as the 440 and 426 cu in (7.2 and 7.0 L) V8s, all with a standard 3-speed manual transmission, except for the 290 bhp (216.3 kW) 383 CID engine, which was available only with the TorqueFlite automatic transmission. A 4-speed manual was optional on all engines except the 225 CID I6 and the 2-barrel 383 CID V8.
